{
  "doc_id": "3426",
  "text": "Fibronectin is a classic example of this type of mechanism, requiring cell-generated tension to polymerize [CITATION_1] . Increased or decreased sites for cell attachment can alter cell behaviours as well as phenotype. Tension or slack within ECM fibrils may also open sites for remodelling, for instance, opening cryptic polymerization sites to reinforce otherwise weak ECM or opening proteolytic sites that to prune overly stiff networks [CITATION_2] . In addition, many growth factors are bound within the ECM [CITATION_3] , and their release may depend on mechanical cues.",
